<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=805699374&t=artid%3df92a7091-f818-47b1-a8f0-5f5b45c9e62e%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=805699374&t=artid%3df92a7091-f818-47b1-a8f0-5f5b45c9e62e%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>“Our plans to go home for the December holidays are ruined because we have to start all over,” said father of three Thozamile Zaliwa.Ndileka Goqa (36) threw her son with disabilities in the canal close by to save him from the fire. With tears in her eyes, the mother of the 13-year-old explained she had no choice.“My son cannot walk and I lost everything because I was trying to save him. It’s very hard to live in a shack with a disabled child. If I had not thought on my feet he would have died,” said Ndileka.Lubabalo Mfihlelwa’s shack did not burn but he asked the government to help. “I am hurt. Most people here lost everything. We still use the bucket system and even the buckets burnt. We have no place to relieve ourselves. We need assistance to be moved from here before we die.”Councillor Buli Madikane said the shacks were built on Sanral land and the City of Cape Town had been fighting for the people to get services.Madikane said Sassa would give the families stipends and Home Affairs would assist with IDs on Monday.Fire and Rescue spokesman Richard Coleman said: “About 100 structures burnt down and one firefighter suffered slight injuries. About 500 people are displaced.”
